# mass-pr-rebase-parallel-agents — History

## v3.0.0 (2026-03-27)

**Changed by:** ProjectScylla sequential wave rebase — 9 PRs in 4 waves with src-layout migration
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added sequential wave execution pattern (Phases 1-4 restructured around waves)
- Added superseded PR detection workflow (check for empty diff after rebase)
- Added structural migration handling (src-layout as "last wave" pattern)
- Added 5 new Failed Attempts: parallel-all-at-once, force-with-lease stale ref, Safety Net blockers, closed PR reopen failure, src-layout-first ordering
- Updated Phase 1 with wave ordering rules and dependency analysis
- Added Phase 4 for structural migrations
- Updated agent configuration to show Myrmidon swarm tiered approach
- Added v3.0.0 session results (9 PRs, 4 waves, 2 hours)

### Why
v2.0.0 used fully parallel rebase — all PRs rebased onto same main snapshot simultaneously. This works when PRs don't overlap, but fails when PRs touch same files (CHANGELOG.md, cli/main.py, pyproject.toml). Later PRs re-conflict when earlier ones merge. Sequential waves solve this: only start Wave N after Wave N-1 PRs have merged to main.

Additionally, the src-layout migration (scylla/ → src/scylla/) conflicted with every other PR. Attempting it first would require every subsequent PR to update paths. Merging it last meant only one PR (the migration itself) needed rework.

### Previous version (v2.0.0) snapshot

```yaml
name: mass-pr-rebase-parallel-agents
description: 'Batch rebase 10-100+ conflicting PRs using parallel sub-agents with worktree isolation and semantic conflict resolution.'
category: ci-cd
date: 2026-03-27
version: 2.0.0
verification: verified-local
```

Key approach: Classify PRs by complexity, batch into parallel agents with worktree isolation, semantic conflict resolution, pixi.lock regeneration. 5 phases: Fix main CI, Classify/Order, Batch Rebase, Fix CI-only, Handle Superseded.

